								<section>
									<h1>For Loops</h1>
									<p>As long as the condition within the loop is true, the curly brackett code block will continue to run.</p>
									<p>Notice how the <b>i</b> variable within the condition itself is set, tested then incremented.</p>
									<a href="http://javascriptbook.com/code/c04/for-loop.html">Duckett online example</a>
									<pre>
										<code class="language-javascript">
											var scores = [24, 32, 17];      // Array of scores
											var arrayLength = scores.length;// Items in array
											var roundNumber = 0;            // Current round
											var msg = '';                   // Message

											// Loop through the items in the array
											for (var i = 0; i < arrayLength; i++) {

											  //Try using a console.log within the loop to visualize it:
												console.log('a');

											  // Arrays are zero based (so 0 is round 1)
											  // Add 1 to the current round
											  roundNumber = (i + 1);

											  // Write the current round to message
											  msg += 'Round ' + roundNumber + ': ';

											  // Get the score from the scores array
											  msg += scores[i] + '<br />';
											}

											document.getElementById('answer').innerHTML = msg;
										</code
									></pre>
								</section>


								<section>
									<h1>While Loops</h1>
									<p>We use the previous for loops when the number of iterations are known. We use while loops when the number of iterations are unknown. </p>
									<p>Simple while loop syntax:</p>
									<pre>
										<code class="language-javascript">
											// When the number of iterations are not known
											while( i < 10)
											{
											    //Some code goes here
											}
										</code>
									</pre>
									<a href="http://javascriptbook.com/code/c04/while-loop.html">Duckett online example</a>
									<pre>
										<code class="language-javascript">
											var i = 1;       // Set counter to 1
											var msg = '';    // Message

											// Store 5 times table in a variable
											while (i < 10) {
											  msg += i + ' x 5 = ' + (i * 5) + '<br />';
											  i++;
											}

											document.getElementById('answer').innerHTML = msg;
										</code
